\item I have checked the data files deposited by the authors. Although they seem complete, I could not find a label/style file for the rasters. That is, since the rasters are in .tif format, I could not identify which land cover class is represented by each number.
  
  \textcolor{blue}{See response to previous comment.}

\item The data repository is sufficient, but lacks online visualization tools or assessment of individual maps.

\end{enumerate}
  
\noindent \textbf{Response to Referee \#2:}

\begin{enumerate}
\item How feasible is it to use the same calibration factors to create the LU/LC of recent years (after 2010)? Because the urbanization was more rigours after 2010. 
  
  \textcolor{blue}{As mentioned in our response to reviewer \#1, a shortcoming of the dataset is that it does not account for temporal variability in the socio-economic covariates (population density, accessibility, distance to roads). This is due to the lack of such datasets for more than one point in time. We would point out that the dataset provides maps between 1960-2010 only, and hence is unaffected by the increase in the rate of urbanization post-2010. Nevertheless, the general point stands and, as mentioned in our response to reviewer \#1, we have added the following sentence to the Usage notes section:}
  
  \textcolor{magenta}{\textit{Users of the dataset should be aware that in the present analysis the explanatory factors of population density, accessibility and distance to roads have been treated as static in time due to the lack of historical, spatially explicit data showing the evolution of these variables during the study period.}}

\item Need little more clarification and validation of picking Indiastat data

  \textcolor{blue}{The Indiastat dataset was selected because it was the only such dataset which provided district level land use/land cover inventory data. Ultimately, the source of the data is the official data compiled by the Directorate of Economics and Statistics. We have extended the description of the dataset in the subsection \emph{Land use and land cover inventory data}, which now reads:}

  \textcolor{magenta}{\textit{The amount of land change in each district and at each time point during the study period was derived from district-level land use/land cover inventory data. In India, data about land use/land cover are collected at the village level on an annual basis and aggregated to district and state administrative levels. The compilation of the village level data is coordinated by the Directorate of Economics and Statistics of India's Ministry of Agriculture. Data for the entire study period, except the period 1993--1997 which for unknown reasons was not available, was purchased from Indiastat (\url{https://www.indiastat.com/}), a commercial organisation which distributes socio-economic data about India. An additional source of district-level survey data for 19 States and Union Territories for the period 1966 to 2009 was obtained from the Icrisat Village Dynamics in South Asia (VDSA) project (\url{http://vdsa.icrisat.ac.in/}). This data originates from the same ultimate source as the Indiastat data but, as part of the VDSA project, has already undergone some data quality assurance and, moreover, includes data for the period 1993--1997.}}

\item Need little more insights about using HILDA for prediction

  \textcolor{blue}{The HILDA model is well described in the literature (see Fuchs et al. (2013, 2015), for example), and has been used previously to reconstruct historical land use change in Europe. It is our opinion that the model is described sufficiently in our manuscript and in the literature to justify its use in the present analysis. If the reviewer had any specific queries or criticisms of the model we would of course be happy to address these in a revised manuscript.}\\

\end{enumerate}

